org.chronos.chronosphere.api

Interface ChronoSphere

  • All Superinterfaces:
    java.lang.AutoCloseable
    All Known Subinterfaces:
    ChronoSphereInternal
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    StandardChronoSphere

    public interface ChronoSphere
extends java.lang.AutoCloseable
    This is the main repository interface, it represents the whole model repository.

    To get an instance of this class, please use the fluent builder API: 

     ChronoSphere repository = ChronoSphere.FACTORY.create() /... settings ... / .build();
    After creating this class, you should set up your EPackages through the methods provided by getEPackageManager(). Then, you can use the various overloads of tx() to create transactions for working with the contents of the repository.

      • tx

        ChronoSphereTransaction tx(long timestamp)
                    throws org.chronos.chronodb.api.exceptions.InvalidTransactionTimestampException
        Produces and returns a new instance of ChronoSphereTransaction on the master branch at the given timestamp.

        Please note that implementations may choose to refuse opening a transaction on certain timestamps, e.g. when the desired timestamp is in the future. In such cases, an InvalidTransactionTimestampException is thrown.

        Note that transactions are in general not thread-safe and must not be shared among threads.

        Parameters:
        timestamp - The timestamp to use. Must not be negative.
        Returns:
        The transaction. Never null.
        Throws:
        org.chronos.chronodb.api.exceptions.InvalidTransactionTimestampException - Thrown if the transaction could not be opened due to an invalid timestamp.

      • batchInsertModelData

        default void batchInsertModelData(java.lang.String xmiContent)
        Batch-inserts the EObject model data from the given XMI content into the master branch of this repository.

        Please remember to register your EPackages before calling this method.

        Only one batch insert process can be active at any point in time. Any other write transactions will be denied while this process is running.

        Parameters:
        xmiContent - The XMI content to load. This string must contain the actual XMI contents. Must not be null, must be syntactically valid XMI.
        See Also:
        batchInsertModelData(File)

      • batchInsertModelData

                                  java.lang.String xmiContent)
        Batch-inserts the EObject model data from the given XMI content into the given branch of this repository.

        Please remember to register your EPackages before calling this method.

        Only one batch insert process can be active at any point in time. Any other write transactions will be denied while this process is running.

        Parameters:
        branch - The branch to load the model elements into. Must not be null, must refer to an existing branch.
        xmiContent - The XMI content to load. This string must contain the actual XMI contents. Must not be null, must be syntactically valid XMI.
        See Also:
        batchInsertModelData(String, File)

        Batch-inserts the given EObject model data into the master branch of this repository.

      • close

        void close()
        Closes this ChronoSphere instance.

        Any further attempt to work with this instance will give rise to an appropriate exception, unless noted explicitly in the method documentation.

        This method is safe to use on closed instances. When called on an already closed instance, this method is a no-op and returns immediately.

        Specified by:

      • getNow

        default long getNow()
        Returns the "now" timestamp, i.e. the timestamp of the latest commit on the repository, on the master branch.

        Requesting a transaction on this timestamp will always deliver a transaction on the "head" revision.

        Returns:
        The "now" timestamp. Will be zero if no commit has been taken place yet, otherwise a positive value.

      • getNow

        long getNow(java.lang.String branchName)
        Returns the "now" timestamp, i.e. the timestamp of the latest commit on the repository, on the given branch.

        Requesting a transaction on this timestamp will always deliver a transaction on the "head" revision.

        Parameters:
        branchName - The name of the branch to retrieve the "now" timestamp for. Must refer to an existing branch. Must not be null.
        Returns:
        The "now" timestamp on the given branch. If no commits have occurred on the branch yet, this method returns zero (master branch) or the branching timestamp (non-master branch), otherwise a positive value.

      • getCommitMetadata

        default java.lang.Object getCommitMetadata(long timestamp)
        Returns the metadata for the commit on the master branch at the given timestamp.

        This search will include origin branches (recursively), if the timestamp is after the branching timestamp.

        Parameters:
        timestamp - The timestamp to get the commit metadata for. Must match the commit timestamp exactly. Must not be negative.
        Returns:
        The commit metadata. May be null if there was no metadata for the commit, or there has not been a commit at the specified branch and timestamp.

      • getCommitMetadata

        java.lang.Object getCommitMetadata(java.lang.String branch,
                                   long timestamp)
        Returns the metadata for the commit on the given branch at the given timestamp.

        This search will include origin branches (recursively), if the timestamp is after the branching timestamp.

        Parameters:
        branch - The branch to search for the commit metadata in. Must not be null.
        timestamp - The timestamp to get the commit metadata for. Must match the commit timestamp exactly. Must not be negative.
        Returns:
        The commit metadata. May be null if there was no metadata for the commit, or there has not been a commit at the specified branch and timestamp.

      • getCommitTimestampsBetween

        default java.util.Iterator<java.lang.Long> getCommitTimestampsBetween(long from,
                                                                      long to)
        Returns an iterator over all timestamps where commits have occurred on the master branch, bounded between from and to, in descending order.

        If the from value is greater than the to value, this method always returns an empty iterator.

        Parameters:
        from - The lower bound of the time range to look for commits in (inclusive). Must not be negative. Must be less than or equal to the timestamp of this transaction.
        to - The upper bound of the time range to look for commits in (inclusive). Must not be negative. Must be less than or equal to the timestamp of this transaction.
        Returns:
        The iterator over the commit timestamps in the given time range, in descending order. May be empty, but never null.

        Returns an iterator over all timestamps where commits have occurred, bounded between from and to.

        If the from value is greater than the to value, this method always returns an empty iterator.

        Parameters:
        branch - The name of the branch to consider. Must not be null, must refer to an existing branch.
        from - The lower bound of the time range to look for commits in (inclusive). Must not be negative. Must be less than or equal to the timestamp of this transaction.
        to - The upper bound of the time range to look for commits in (inclusive). Must not be negative. Must be less than or equal to the timestamp of this transaction.
        order - The order of the returned timestamps. Must not be null.
        Returns:
        The iterator over the commit timestamps in the given time range. May be empty, but never null.

      • getCommitMetadataBetween

        default java.util.Iterator<java.util.Map.Entry<java.lang.Long,java.lang.Object>> getCommitMetadataBetween(long from,
                                                                                                          long to)
        Returns an iterator over the entries of commit timestamp and associated metadata on the master branch, bounded between from and to, in descending order.

        If the from value is greater than the to value, this method always returns an empty iterator.

        Please keep in mind that some commits may not have any metadata attached. In this case, the value component of the Map.Entry will be set to null.

        Parameters:
        from - The lower bound of the time range to look for commits in (inclusive). Must not be negative. Must be less than or equal to the timestamp of this transaction.
        to - The upper bound of the time range to look for commits in (inclusive). Must not be negative. Must be less than or equal to the timestamp of this transaction.
        Returns:
        An iterator over the commits in the given time range in descending order. The contained entries have the timestamp as the key component and the associated metadata as their value component (which may be null). May be empty, but never null.

      • getCommitTimestampsPaged

        default java.util.Iterator<java.lang.Long> getCommitTimestampsPaged(long minTimestamp,
                                                                    long maxTimestamp,
                                                                    int pageSize,
                                                                    int pageIndex,
                                                                    org.chronos.chronodb.api.Order order)
        Returns an iterator over commit timestamps on the master branch in a paged fashion.

        For example, calling getCommitTimestampsPaged(10000, 100, 0, Order.DESCENDING) will give the latest 100 commit timestamps that have occurred before timestamp 10000. Calling getCommitTimestampsPaged(123456, 200, 2, Order.DESCENDING will return 200 commit timestamps, skipping the 400 latest commit timestamps, which are smaller than 123456.

        Parameters:
        minTimestamp - The minimum timestamp to consider (inclusive). All lower timestamps will be excluded from the pagination. Must be less than or equal to the timestamp of this transaction.
        maxTimestamp - The highest timestamp to consider (inclusive). All higher timestamps will be excluded from the pagination. Must be less than or equal to the timestamp of this transaction.
        pageSize - The size of the page, i.e. the maximum number of elements allowed to be contained in the resulting iterator. Must be greater than zero.
        pageIndex - The index of the page to retrieve. Must not be negative.
        order - The desired ordering for the commit timestamps
        Returns:
        An iterator that contains the commit timestamps for the requested page. Never null, may be empty. If the requested page does not exist, this iterator will always be empty.

      • getCommitMetadataPaged

        default java.util.Iterator<java.util.Map.Entry<java.lang.Long,java.lang.Object>> getCommitMetadataPaged(long minTimestamp,
                                                                                                        long maxTimestamp,
                                                                                                        int pageSize,
                                                                                                        int pageIndex,
                                                                                                        org.chronos.chronodb.api.Order order)
        Returns an iterator over commit timestamps and associated metadata on the master branch in a paged fashion.

        For example, calling getCommitTimestampsPaged(10000, 100, 0, Order.DESCENDING) will give the latest 100 commit timestamps that have occurred before timestamp 10000. Calling getCommitTimestampsPaged(123456, 200, 2, Order.DESCENDING will return 200 commit timestamps, skipping the 400 latest commit timestamps, which are smaller than 123456.

        The Entries returned by the iterator always have the commit timestamp as their first component and the metadata associated with this commit as their second component. The second component can be null if the commit was executed without providing metadata.

        Parameters:
        minTimestamp - The minimum timestamp to consider (inclusive). All lower timestamps will be excluded from the pagination. Must be less than or equal to the timestamp of this transaction.
        maxTimestamp - The highest timestamp to consider. All higher timestamps will be excluded from the pagination. Must be less than or equal to the timestamp of this transaction.
        pageSize - The size of the page, i.e. the maximum number of elements allowed to be contained in the resulting iterator. Must be greater than zero.
        pageIndex - The index of the page to retrieve. Must not be negative.
        order - The desired ordering for the commit timestamps
        Returns:
        An iterator that contains the commits for the requested page. Never null, may be empty. If the requested page does not exist, this iterator will always be empty.
